üîπ What is an OBJECT Type in Oracle SQL / PL/SQL?

An OBJECT type is a user-defined datatype that allows you to group multiple related attributes (columns) into a single logical unit, similar to a class in programming.





üîπ Step 1Ô∏è‚É£ Create an OBJECT Type

(Each attribute = one column)

CREATE OR REPLACE TYPE skill_obj AS OBJECT (
  skill_name VARCHAR2(50),
  experience NUMBER,
  level       VARCHAR2(20)
);
/


‚úî Each attribute becomes a column
‚úî Reusable across tables

üîπ Step 2Ô∏è‚É£ Create Nested Table of OBJECT Type
CREATE OR REPLACE TYPE skill_tab IS TABLE OF skill_obj;
/

üîπ Step 3Ô∏è‚É£ Create Table Using Object Collection
CREATE TABLE employees (
  emp_id   NUMBER PRIMARY KEY,
  emp_name VARCHAR2(50),
  skills   skill_tab
)
NESTED TABLE skills STORE AS emp_skills_nt;

üîπ Step 4Ô∏è‚É£ Insert Data (Multiple Columns)
INSERT INTO employees VALUES (
  101,
  'Dharma',
  skill_tab(
    skill_obj('PLSQL', 5, 'ADVANCED'),
    skill_obj('Redis', 3, 'INTERMEDIATE'),
    skill_obj('MongoDB', 4, 'ADVANCED')
  )
);

üîπ Step 5Ô∏è‚É£ SELECT (Now You Get Multiple Columns)
SELECT e.emp_id,
       e.emp_name,
       t.skill_name,
       t.experience,
       t.level
FROM employees e,
     TABLE(e.skills) t;

‚úÖ Output
101 | Dharma | PLSQL   | 5 | ADVANCED
101 | Dharma | Redis   | 3 | INTERMEDIATE
101 | Dharma | MongoDB | 4 | ADVANCED

üîπ UPDATE One Column Inside Object
UPDATE TABLE (
  SELECT e.skills
  FROM employees e
  WHERE e.emp_id = 101
)
SET experience = 6
WHERE skill_name = 'PLSQL';

üîπ DELETE One Skill
DELETE FROM TABLE (
  SELECT e.skills
  FROM employees e
  WHERE e.emp_id = 101
)
WHERE skill_name = 'Redis';
